<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Common Mistakes When Choosing a Heat Mat</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Choosing only by size without checking tray fit:</strong> awkward setups are harder to use well.</li>
    <li><strong>Buying for every crop instead of the crops that need it most:</strong> peppers usually justify the decision more than tomatoes do.</li>
    <li><strong>Assuming a thermostat is always required:</strong> sometimes it helps a lot, but not every simple setup needs it.</li>
    <li><strong>Trying to use one undersized mat for too many trays:</strong> selective use often works better than overcrowding the mat.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The best heat mat setup is the one that matches your trays, your room, and the crops that actually benefit most from added warmth.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="calloutBox">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Should Actually Buy</h2>

  <p>
    For most home gardeners, buy a standard tray-sized heat mat that fits your seed-starting trays well and provides steady bottom warmth during germination. If peppers are a major part of your setup or your room runs cool, make sure the mat can work with a thermostat or comes in a thermostat-ready setup.
  </p>

  <p>
    Tomatoes will usually do well on the same mat, but peppers are the crop that should drive the decision. In most cases, the best heat mat for both is the one that handles peppers well without turning the system into something more complicated than it needs to be.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Buy the heat mat that solves the pepper problem first. Tomatoes usually fit into that answer just fine.
  </p>
